    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! On a student loan, as you make monthly payments, part of your payment goes towards the interest, and the rest goes towards reducing the principal. With a declining balance, the interest is calculated based on the remaining principal. As you pay more towards the principal, the interest charged will decrease since it's being calculated on a lower balance. This is why you may notice that your principal isn't decreasing as much as expected when you're paying a fixed amount monthly.",
