      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still feels like the interest is just eating up most of my money at first. is there a specific way to calculate exactly how much of my next payment is going to interest vs principal? like what formula should i be using?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! To determine how much of your payment goes towards interest and how much goes towards reducing the principal, you can use the following formula for each payment period:\n\nInterest for the period = Remaining Principal x Periodic Interest Rate\n\nPrincipal for the period = Total Monthly Payment - Interest for the period\n\nHere, the Periodic Interest Rate is the annual interest rate divided by the number of payments per year (usually 12 for monthly payments). As you continue to make payments, the interest portion will decrease while the principal portion will increase, because you're reducing the outstanding balance more each month. Keep in mind that this calculation is a simplified version and actual loan amortization schedules can be more complex, but this gives you a good idea of how the funds are allocated.",
